I ) Data preparation & exploration:¶

A. Problem statement¶

  • The data set: clients of Delta Bank.
  • Data for each client: Attrition_Flag, Customer_Age, Gender, Dependent_count, Education_Level, Marital_Status, Income_Category, Card_Category, Months_on_book, Total_Relationship_Count, Months_Inactive_12_mon, Contacts_Count_12_mon, Credit_Limit, Total_Used_Bal, Total_Unused_Bal, Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1, Total_Trans_Amt, Total_Trans_Ct, Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1 and Avg_Utilization_Ratio.
  • Objective: Find the most probable clients that will leave the company.

Comments:¶

1) Customer Age: Clients between 40 and 50 are more likely to churn.¶

2) Dependent Count: Clients that have 3 family members are more likely to churn.¶

3) Months on Book: Clients with a total relationship duration with the bank of 36 months are more likely to churn.¶

4) Total Relationship Count: Clients that have 3 products in portfolio are more likely to churn.¶

5) Months Inactive 12 Mon: Clients that made no payments for 3 months are more likely to churn.¶

6) Contacts Count 12 Mon: Clients that have interacted with the bank for 3 months are more likely to churn.¶

7) Credit Limit: Clients that have a limit of 2K dollars aprox. on the credit card are more likely to churn.¶

8) Total Used Bal: Clients that didn't use the credit card at all are more likely to churn.¶

9) Total Unused Bal: Clients that have a remaining of 2K dollars aprox. unused on their credit cards are more likely to churn.¶

In [689]:
def censoring_outliers(dataframe, column):
    q1 = dataframe[column].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = dataframe[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = q3 - q1
    lower_limit = q1 - 3 * IQR
    upper_limit = q3 + 3 * IQR
    dataframe[column] = np.where(dataframe[column] < lower_limit, lower_limit, np.where(dataframe[column] > upper_limit, upper_limit, dataframe[column]))
In [690]:
for variable in heavy_affected_by_outliers:
    censoring_outliers(data, variable)

4.2 Lift and Gain analysis¶

In [753]:
# Declare an empty DataFrame
lift_gain_report = pd.DataFrame()

# Add y_test in DataFrame
lift_gain_report['y_test'] = y_test

# STEP 1 #
# Add predict probabilities for class 1 in DataFrame
lift_gain_report['Predicted Probabilities'] = y_predict_proba_class_1

# Order probabilities in ascending order
lift_gain_report['Probabilities Rank'] = lift_gain_report['Predicted Probabilities'].rank(method = 'first', ascending = True, pct = True)

# STEP 2 #
# Calculate decile group
lift_gain_report['Decile group'] = np.floor((1 - lift_gain_report['Probabilities Rank']) * 10) + 1

# STEP 3 #
# Group observations by decile
lift_gain_report['Number of observations'] = 1
lift_gain_report = lift_gain_report.groupby(['Decile group']).sum().reset_index()

# Cumulative number of observations
lift_gain_report['Cumulative no. of observations'] = lift_gain_report['Number of observations'].cumsum()

# Cumulative percentaje of observations
lift_gain_report['Cumulative % of no. of observations'] = lift_gain_report['Cumulative no. of observations'] / lift_gain_report['Cumulative no. of observations'].max()

# STEP 4 #
# Calculate number of positives cumulative
lift_gain_report['Cumulative no. of positives'] = lift_gain_report['y_test'].cumsum()

# STEP 5 #
# Calculate cumulative % of positives ( GAIN )
lift_gain_report['Gain'] = lift_gain_report['Cumulative no. of positives'] / lift_gain_report['Cumulative no. of positives'].max()

# STEP 6 #
# Calculate LIFT
lift_gain_report['Lift'] = lift_gain_report['Gain'] / lift_gain_report['Cumulative % of no. of observations']

4) Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1: Probability for a client to churn is higher if the change in transaction amount is moderate. For the client not to churn, he needs to have a bigger change in transaction amount.¶

5) Total_Relationship_Count: Probability for a client to churn is higher if the client has less products in portfolio.¶
